Anonymous Sun 30 Aug 2020 22:57:30 No.32482825 Report
Quoted By: >>32482895
>>32471414
Shit man you're too kind. I hope nobody minds if I explain.
I start with a perspective line and usually a reference to work off of. For the loka vs ruby pic I found a postcard while the house in the loka comic is based on a picture I took. Then I just make a brick with similar dimensions to the thing being referenced by having lines that converge on two or three points.
Certain lines, usually triangles, I end up winging such as the shape or edge of the roof. the proper way to do it would be to make a 3d plane, divide it in half, have the point of the triangle going there, carve and extend the plane into a 3d triangular prism.
That's really what I do, either make lines converge on a point and cut them or carve bricks. Compare to the reference and if it doesnt look good correct it. It's primitive trial and error and suffers from a lack of foresight that a better use of a perspective
Lines could prevent. You can see if you compare the great perspective pieces of murle.
The rendering is a lot of the same. I use the selection tool to select a certain surface of my form. Then have lines converging onto a single point and then subdivide or spruce up with verticals. To differentiate between surfaces I sometimes use a different tool, like I used a disney pencil brush for the shingles.
And sometimes such as for the railing made of planks I do it by hand and have the lines converge closer the farther from the viewer the planks are.
I'm still learning and I hope I can get more elaborate with my designs, but I'm so greatful think they're impressive. Have a goodnight :)

>>32493566
As others have said said, the colors are hard to read. Light blue and orange are complementary colors that can contrast unpleasantly to the human eye. Yellow is complementary to blue, by the way, so you'd be better off changing that one too. Also, I'd use Gimp/Paint.net/Photoshop instead of Paint (my assumption), since it makes aligning, justifying and word wrapping the text way easier, ensuring straight lines and better balance. Also, as a subjective note, the story sort of ends before getting to the good part, making it more of a tease than anything else

>>32494116
Again, the text is a bit messy in its positioning, like the last one. Funnily enough, this one almost skips the setup to get right to the action, which can also be a negative. You want a bit of tease as a lead-up, usually, just like sex is better with foreplay. These are mostly technical details, but smut is very subjective and it's hard for me to give any "objective" advice for it. You'd need feedback from multiple people to see where you resonate and where you don't
